.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="355ED367FF9E8D5D3827FA03FD34FE3F" blockId="7.[809,1426,1428,1879]" lastBlockId="11.[145,761,197,403]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="1323" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319">
<emphasis id="07950F75FF9E8D513827FA03FC12FA05" box="[809,916,1428,1449]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319">Remarks:</emphasis>
Genetic differentiation between populations from the Iberian Peninsula (Alicante Province) and Ibiza Island is low, with a mean uncorrected 
<emphasis id="07950F75FF9E8D513827FA67FCB1F9A9" box="[809,823,1520,1541]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319">p</emphasis>
-distance of 0.6% in 
<emphasis id="07950F75FF9E8D513F20FA67FBEEF9A9" box="[1070,1128,1520,1541]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319">Cox1</emphasis>
and identical sequences in all the analysed nuclear markers. This evidence, together with the broad geographical range in the Iberian Peninsula, from at least Cartagena (
<collectingRegion id="F7251D85FF9E8D513E3AF9DBFA0FF9CE" box="[1332,1417,1612,1634]" country="Spain" name="Murcia" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319">Murcia</collectingRegion>
) in the south to Carcagente (
<collectingRegion id="F7251D85FF9E8D513F8CF9FDFB6DF92C" box="[1154,1259,1642,1664]" country="Spain" name="Comunitat Valenciana" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319">Valencia</collectingRegion>
) in the north (
<bibRefCitation id="5170AE96FF9E8D51383CF91EFC7CF932" author="Schmolzer K" box="[818,1018,1673,1695]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319" pagination="1 - 161" refId="ref19120" refString="Schmolzer K. 1971. Die Landisopoden der Iberischen Halbinsel. Monografias de Ciencia Moderna 80: 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="1971">Schmölzer, 1971</bibRefCitation>
), suggests that the origin of the insular populations in Ibiza is recent. The latest terrestrial connection between the Iberian Peninsula and Ibiza dates from the Messinian (
<bibRefCitation id="5170AE96FF9E8D513FF4F971FCE5F8B5" author="Bover P &amp; Quintana J &amp; Alcover JA" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319" pagination="135 - 144" refId="ref16773" refString="Bover P, Quintana J, Alcover JA. 2008. Three islands, three worlds: paleogeography and evolution of the vertebrate fauna from the Balearic Islands. Quaternary International 182: 135 - 144." type="journal article" year="2008">
Bover 
<emphasis id="07950F75FF9E8D513E45F971FA0CF956" box="[1355,1418,1765,1787]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319">et al.</emphasis>
, 2008
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="5170AE96FF9E8D51387BF893FBBBF8B5" author="Mas G &amp; Maillard A &amp; Alcover JA &amp; Fornos JJ &amp; Bover P &amp; Torres-Roig E" box="[885,1085,1796,1817]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319" pagination="527 - 530" refId="ref17962" refString="Mas G, Maillard A, Alcover JA, Fornos JJ, Bover P, Torres-Roig E. 2018. Terrestrial colonization of the Balearic Islands: new evidence for the Mediterranean sea-level drawdown during the Messinian Salinity Crisis. Geology 46: 527 - 530." type="journal article" year="2018">
Mas 
<emphasis id="07950F75FF9E8D5138BCF893FC77F8B5" box="[946,1009,1796,1817]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1319">et al.</emphasis>
, 2018
</bibRefCitation>
); therefore, colonization of the island must have occurred by overseas rafting dispersal or associated with human activity, which has been documented for other organisms present in this archipelago (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="5170AE96FF928D5D3A8CFF73FD20FF56" author="Gomez K &amp; Espadaler X" box="[386,678,228,250]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323" pagination="225 - 233" refId="ref17555" refString="Gomez K, Espadaler X. 2006. Exotic ants (Hymenoptera: Formicidae) in the Balearic Islands. Myrmecologische Nachrichten 8: 225 - 233." type="journal article" year="2006">Gómez &amp; Espadaler, 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="5170AE96FF928D5D39BDFF73FE94FEB4" author="Podda L &amp; Arguimbau P &amp; Mascia F &amp; Mayoral Garcia-Berlanga O &amp; Bacchetta G" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323" pagination="31 - 45" refId="ref18164" refString="Podda L, Fraga i Arguimbau P, Mascia F, Mayoral Garcia-Berlanga O, Bacchetta G. 2011. Comparison of the invasive alien flora in continental islands: Sardinia (Italy) and Balearic Islands (Spain). Rendiconti Lincei 22: 31 - 45." type="journal article" year="2011">
Podda 
<emphasis id="07950F75FF928D5D3B9FFE94FF4DFEBB" box="[145,203,258,280]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323">et al.</emphasis>
, 2011
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="5170AE96FF928D5D3A2EFE94FE7FFEB4" author="Santos X &amp; Ayllon E &amp; Arribas O &amp; Bertolero A &amp; Bosch J &amp; Cabido C &amp; Carranza S &amp; Carretero MA &amp; Diaz-Paniagua C &amp; Egea-Serrano A &amp; Garin-Barrio I &amp; Gimenez A &amp; Gosa A &amp; Gracia E &amp; Guicking D &amp; Llorente GA &amp; Martinez-Solano I &amp; Mateo JA &amp; Montori A &amp; Palomar G &amp; Perera A &amp; Pinya S &amp; Pretus JL &amp; Pujol-Buxo E &amp; Rato C &amp; Recuero E &amp; Azkue I &amp; Silva-Rocha I &amp; Vasconcelos R &amp; Velo-Anton G &amp; Voros J &amp; Pleguezuelos JM" box="[288,505,258,280]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323" pagination="98 - 108" refId="ref18546" refString="Santos X, Ayllon E, Arribas O, Bertolero A, Bosch J, Cabido C, Carranza S, Carretero MA, Diaz-Paniagua C, Egea-Serrano A, Garin-Barrio I, Gimenez A, Gosa A, Gracia E, Guicking D, Llorente GA, Martinez-Solano I, Mateo JA, Montori A, Palomar G, Perera A, Pinya S, Pretus JL, Pujol-Buxo E, Rato C, Recuero E, Sanz- Azkue I, Silva-Rocha I, Vasconcelos R, Velo-Anton G, Voros J, Pleguezuelos JM. 2015. Sintesis de las introducciones de anfibios y reptiles en Espana. Boletin de la Asociacion Herpetologica Espanola 26: 98 - 108." type="journal article" year="2015">
Santos 
<emphasis id="07950F75FF928D5D3A76FE94FE35FEBB" box="[376,435,258,280]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323">et al.</emphasis>
, 2015
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="F2E1A8E4FF928D5D391EFE95FE97FE9B" baseAuthorityName="Budde-Lund" baseAuthorityYear="1885" class="Malacostraca" family="Armadillidiidae" genus="Cristarmadillidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="muricatum">
<emphasis id="07950F75FF928D5D391EFE95FE97FE9B" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="1323">Cristarmadillidium muricatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a troglophilic species, with most known populations inhabiting karstic caves, but it is also present in limestone soils not associated with caves, as in the case of the studied population from Ibiza.
</paragraph>
